title: Computer Augmented Environments using Everyday Cushiony Objects
title_en: Computer Augmented Environments using Everyday Cushiony Objects
abstract: 本研究は日常にあるクッション状オブジェクトを計測・拡張してコンピュータ支援環境の入力装置とすることを目的としている。 本研究はクッション内部に圧力/荷重センサや加速度センサ、小型マイコンと無線モジュールを組み込み、PCとLEDによる入出力連携を行うプロトタイプを構築した。 本研究は出力電圧と加重の関係を計測する実験により、クッション状オブジェクトが小さな重さ変化を検出可能であることを示した。
abstract_en: This study aims to instrument everyday cushiony objects to serve as input devices for computer-augmented environments. This study built a prototype by embedding pressure/load sensors, accelerometers, a microcontroller, and a wireless module in cushions and used PC and LED feedback for input-output integration. This study measured the relationship between output voltage and applied weight and demonstrated that cushiony objects can detect small weight changes.
positioning_summary: 本研究は日常のクッション状オブジェクトをコンピュータ支援環境に組み込むことで身体接触を介した自然な入力手段の実現を目指す入力装置研究の領域に位置づけられる。 本研究は家庭や公共空間での利用を想定し、柔らかい触感を扱う既存の硬質デバイスが苦手とする領域のギャップを埋める点でHCI研究やインタラクション設計者を対象として位置づけられる。
positioning_summary_en: This study is positioned in the area of input device research aiming to realize natural touch-based input by integrating everyday cushiony objects into computer-augmented environments. This study is positioned for HCI researchers and interaction designers because it targets usage in home and public spaces and aims to fill the gap that rigid devices have when handling soft tactile properties.
purpose_summary: 本研究の目的は日常的なクッション状オブジェクトを入力デバイス化して座る・押すなどの身体行為を検出し、日常環境におけるインタラクションを拡張することである。 本研究は家庭や公共空間でクッションを日常的に使う一般利用者を対象に、柔らかい触感を利用した自然な入力手段を提供することを目指している。
purpose_summary_en: The purpose of this study is to convert everyday cushiony objects into input devices that detect body actions such as sitting and pressing and thereby extend interactions in everyday environments. The purpose of this study is to target general users who use cushions in homes and public spaces and to provide natural input methods that leverage soft tactile properties.
method_summary: 本研究はクッション内部に圧力/荷重センサや3軸加速度センサを組み込み、小型マイコン基板と無線モジュールで信号を取得・送信しPCとLEDでフィードバックするプロトタイプを構築した。 本研究はADC値(0–1023)を±50のレンジへ線形変換してX/Y/Z軸データを処理し、複数のセンサ型番と小型バッテリを組み合わせて出力電圧と加重の関係を取得する設計を用いた。
method_summary_en: This study built a prototype that embeds pressure/load sensors and a 3-axis accelerometer inside cushions and uses a microcontroller board and a wireless module to acquire and transmit signals with PC and LED feedback. This study used ADC values (0–1023) linearly mapped to a ±50 range for X/Y/Z data processing and combined multiple sensor types and a small battery to obtain the relationship between output voltage and applied weight.
evaluation_summary: 本研究の評価は加重を変化させながらクッションの出力電圧を計測して「出力電圧対重量」の関係をプロットする実験で行われた。 本研究の実験ではクッション状オブジェクトの最小検出重さが約6.0 g程度であることが確認され、参加者8名によるPC上での操作実験も実施されているが抜粋部では詳細な結果は記載されていない。
evaluation_summary_en: The evaluation in this study measured cushion output voltage while varying applied weight and plotted the relationship between output voltage and weight. The evaluation in this study confirmed a minimum detectable weight of about 6.0 g and also included a PC-based user study with 8 participants, although detailed results are not provided in the excerpt.

Title: Computer Augmented Environments using Everyday Cushiony Objects
Authors: Gota Kakehi, Yuta Sugiura, Maki Sugimoto, Masahiko Inami
Year: 2010
Abstract: This study aims to instrument everyday cushiony objects to serve as input devices for computer-augmented environments. This study built a prototype by embedding pressure/load sensors, accelerometers, a microcontroller, and a wireless module in cushions and used PC and LED feedback for input-output integration. This study measured the relationship between output voltage and applied weight and demonstrated that cushiony objects can detect small weight changes.
Positioning Summary: This study is positioned in the area of input device research aiming to realize natural touch-based input by integrating everyday cushiony objects into computer-augmented environments. This study is positioned for HCI researchers and interaction designers because it targets usage in home and public spaces and aims to fill the gap that rigid devices have when handling soft tactile properties.
Purpose Summary: The purpose of this study is to convert everyday cushiony objects into input devices that detect body actions such as sitting and pressing and thereby extend interactions in everyday environments. The purpose of this study is to target general users who use cushions in homes and public spaces and to provide natural input methods that leverage soft tactile properties.
Method Summary: This study built a prototype that embeds pressure/load sensors and a 3-axis accelerometer inside cushions and uses a microcontroller board and a wireless module to acquire and transmit signals with PC and LED feedback. This study used ADC values (0–1023) linearly mapped to a ±50 range for X/Y/Z data processing and combined multiple sensor types and a small battery to obtain the relationship between output voltage and applied weight.
Evaluation Summary: The evaluation in this study measured cushion output voltage while varying applied weight and plotted the relationship between output voltage and weight. The evaluation in this study confirmed a minimum detectable weight of about 6.0 g and also included a PC-based user study with 8 participants, although detailed results are not provided in the excerpt.
